05014nam a22007815i 9780520921405DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1241853232  a97805209214057 a10.1525/97805209214052doi  a(DE-B1597)542550  a(OCoLC)1153536251  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aNA1996b.W64 1999eb 7aARC0050002bisacsh04a720/.23/732211 aWoods, Mary N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Craft to Profession :bThe Practice of Architecture in Nineteenth-Century America /cMary N. Woods.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b51 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER I. THE FIRST PROFESSIONAL -- tCHAPTER 2. PROFESSIONAL ORGANIZATIONS AND AGENDAS -- tCHAPTER 3. TRAINING AND EDUCATION -- tCHAPTER 4. FORMS AND SETTINGS OF PRACTICE -- tCHAPTER 5. ASSISTANTS, RIVALS, AND COLLABORATORS -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first in-depth study of how the architectural profession emerged in early American history. Mary Woods dispels the prevailing notion that the profession developed under the leadership of men formally schooled in architecture as an art during the late nineteenth century. Instead, she cites several instances in the early 1800s of craftsmen-builders who shifted their identity to that of professional architects. While struggling to survive as designers and supervisors of construction projects, these men organized professional societies and worked for architectural education, appropriate compensation, and accreditation.In such leading architectural practitioners as B. Henry Latrobe, Alexander J. Davis, H. H. Richardson, Louis Sullivan, and Stanford White, Woods sees collaborators, partners, merchandisers, educators, and lobbyists rather than inspired creators. She documents their contributions as well as those, far less familiar, of women architects and people of color in the profession's early days.Woods's extensive research yields a remarkable range of archival materials: correspondence among carpenters; 200-year-old lawsuits; architect-client spats; the organization of craft guilds, apprenticeships, university programs, and correspondence schools; and the structure of architectural practices, labor unions, and the building industry. In presenting a more accurate composite of the architectural profession's history, Woods lays a foundation for reclaiming the profession's past and recasting its future. Her study will appeal not only to architects, but also to historians, sociologists, and readers with an interest in architecture's place in America today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitectural practicexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aArchitectural practicezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  a19th century.  aamerican history.  aarchitect-client relations.  aarchitectural education.  aarchitectural engineering.  aarchitectural profession.  aarchitecture art theory.  aarchitecture.  abuilding design.  aconstruction.  acontributions.  ahistory.  ainspired creators.  alawsuits.  aleading architects.  alegal complications.  aprofessional architects.  asociologists.  asociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021494140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520921405?locatt=mode:legacy